T1  - Market Returns and Interim Risk in Mergers
AU  - Heath, Davidson
AU  - Mitchell, Mark
Y1  - 2022/02/14
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2023/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4315
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4315
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 617
EP  - 635
VL  - 69
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A primary concern in mergers and acquisitions is the risk the deal may be cancelled before it is completed. We document that ?interim risk? varies asymmetrically with the aggregate market return. Deals tend to be renegotiated when the market rises, but cancelled when the market crashes. These effects are conditional on the method of payment and the contracting stage of the deal, consistent with a mechanism of ex post renegotiation. Variation in interim risk over time alters the method of payment in mergers and the firms that are targeted and acquired.This paper was accepted by Victoria Ivashina, finance.Supplemental Material: The e-companion and data are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4315.
AB  - A primary concern in mergers and acquisitions is the risk the deal may be cancelled before it is completed. We document that ?interim risk? varies asymmetrically with the aggregate market return. Deals tend to be renegotiated when the market rises, but cancelled when the market crashes. These effects are conditional on the method of payment and the contracting stage of the deal, consistent with a mechanism of ex post renegotiation. Variation in interim risk over time alters the method of payment in mergers and the firms that are targeted and acquired.This paper was accepted by Victoria Ivashina, finance.Supplemental Material: The e-companion and data are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4315.
